7353741662511811883.voice_to_text: Some people are still confused as to why Starbucks is getting boycotted, and I'm here to tell you why and give you the details. So on October 7th, Starbucks is workers union, also known as Starbucks Workers United, posted a pro Palestine tweet expressing their solidary with Palestine. Few days after the tweet, Florida Republicans, including US Senator Rick Scott, called for a boycott of Starbucks. The Orthodox Chamber of Commerce also called for a boycott of Starbucks, saying that drinking a cup of Starbucks was drinking a cup of Jewish blood. On the same day as these calls for a boycott, Starbucks leadership said that they disagreed with the union's views and statement. Former Starbucks CEO Howard Schulz met with the CEO and founder of the Orthodox Jewish Chamber to discuss the ongoing support of Israel and the condemnation of the union stores that support Palestine. The CEO of the Orthodox Jewish Chamber suggested to shows that he should close down the stores. Colts explained that it would be illegal for him to do so, but expressed his desire to close down every union store and terminate all the employees. The chamber suggested that Starbucks should take legal action, and then the chamber and Starbucks work together to release a list of all 300 Union stores and their addresses, putting all of these employees at risk. On October 18th, Starbucks sued the union for trademark infringement, demanding that Starbucks Workers United stop using Starbucks in their name and to also stop Using any other identifying symbols, Starbucks Workers United then sued Starbucks because the company has stated and implied that the union supports terrorism and violence. Because of Starbucks's ongoing support for Israel and them suing the union after a pro Palestine tweet, many people and customers then started calling for a boycott on Starbucks. So before your next Starbucks trip, think, is this a company that I really wanna support?
